    'hanoi.overviewTitle': 'Overview',
    'hanoi.overviewP1': 'This project didn\'t start with a question about hotels. It started with a constraint: I wanted a dataset that reflected reality, messy, incomplete, full of edge cases, rather than something pre-cleaned and ready-made.',
    'hanoi.overviewP2': 'Booking.com fit that brief, and Hanoi\'s tourism-driven market gave me something worth analyzing once the data existed.',
    'hanoi.overviewP3': 'What I didn\'t expect was that building the dataset would turn out to be the hardest, and most instructive, part of the project.',
    'hanoi.overviewP4': 'The eventual research question, which guest experience dimensions most consistently underperform relative to the overall rating, and whether this differs by property type, only became askable once the dataset existed.',

    'hanoi.challengeTitle': 'The 750-Result Wall',
    'hanoi.challengeP1': 'Booking.com caps search results at roughly 750 listings per query. Hanoi has somewhere around 4,100 active listings. A direct scrape would only ever surface a fraction of the market, and an arbitrary fraction at that, shaped by whatever Booking\'s default ranking happened to favor.',
    'hanoi.challengeP2': 'I spent the first few days just understanding why the count stopped at 750. I eventually traced it to the \'load more\' button disappearing at that point, a soft platform limit rather than a technical one. That reframed the problem: this wasn\'t a scraping problem, it was a sampling problem.',

    'hanoi.collectionTitle': 'Reverse-Engineering the Ranking System',
    'hanoi.collectionSub': 'Turning one query into many',
    'hanoi.collectionP1': 'If one query couldn\'t surface the full market, I needed multiple queries that each surfaced a different slice of it, with minimal overlap. The breakthrough was noticing that Booking lets you sort listings by rating ascending and descending: each direction returns a different 750-listing window from opposite ends of the distribution.',
    'hanoi.collectionP2': 'Combined with filters for district, property type, and star rating, I built a cartesian product of query parameters, where every combination of filters and sort direction became its own scrape pass. It took 3-4 days to land on this approach, and most of that time wasn\'t writing code; it was reading scrape logs to tell whether a pass was surfacing new listings or just re-scraping the same ones from a different angle.',

    'hanoi.validationTitle': 'From 3,795 to 2,044',
    'hanoi.validationP1': 'Before any analysis, I checked whether the collected data could actually support it. Listings with fewer than 10 reviews were dropped, since there were too few data points for a stable sub-score.',
    'hanoi.validationP2': 'One sub-dimension, free Wi-Fi, had 58% missing values. Rather than assume missing meant \'no Wi-Fi,\' I treated this as a platform display inconsistency rather than a real signal, and excluded it from the analysis.',
    'hanoi.validationP3': 'I also spot-checked individual listings to confirm the overall score isn\'t simply an average of the seven sub-scores. It isn\'t, which is what makes a \'gap\' metric (overall minus sub-score) meaningful rather than redundant.',

    'hanoi.discoveryTitle': 'Analysis',
    'hanoi.discoverySub': 'Measuring relative strength, not absolute score',
    'hanoi.discoveryP1': 'Rather than ranking dimensions by their raw scores, I calculated a gap for each one: the overall score minus the sub-score. A more negative gap means that dimension outperforms the overall rating, a relative strength. A gap closer to zero means the dimension contributes less to the guest\'s sense that the property exceeded expectations.',
    'hanoi.discoveryP2': 'gap = overall score − sub-score\nMore negative values indicate dimensions that outperform overall guest expectations.\nValues closer to zero indicate dimensions that contribute less to perception advantages.',

    'hanoi.findingTitle': 'Key Finding',
    'hanoi.findingSub': 'Facilities vs Staff',
    'hanoi.findingP1': 'One result stood out. Facilities, the dimension requiring the most visible operational investment, was the one that least exceeded guest expectations.',
    'hanoi.findingP2': 'Facilities barely exceeded the overall score, while Staff outperformed it by a wide margin.',
    'hanoi.findingP3': 'The difference between the two dimensions was larger than any other contrast in the dataset.',

    'hanoi.investigationTitle': 'Investigation',
    'hanoi.investigationSub': 'Looking Deeper by Property Type',
    'hanoi.investigationP1': 'At that point, I wanted to understand whether the Facilities pattern was consistent across different accommodation types.',
    'hanoi.investigationP2': 'Breaking the data down by property type revealed an important exception.',

    'hanoi.implicationsTitle': 'Implications',
    'hanoi.implicationsP1': 'The data suggests service quality, not physical amenities, is the clearest source of perception advantage in Hanoi\'s accommodation market. This doesn\'t mean facilities don\'t matter in absolute terms (ratings remain high), but they contribute comparatively little to exceeding what guests already expect.',
    'hanoi.implicationsP2': 'Location\'s strong negative gap (-0.522) reinforces guest intuition about its importance, but it also points to something more useful: even a property in a weaker location can meaningfully close that gap through staff quality. Location isn\'t destiny; it\'s a starting condition that service can offset.',
    'hanoi.implicationsP3': 'Breaking the data down by property type revealed one exception: homestays are the only segment where Facilities slightly exceeds expectations (+0.031), likely because guest expectations for amenities in a homestay start lower to begin with.',
    'hanoi.implicationsP4': 'For an operator deciding where to allocate a limited improvement budget, the data points toward staff training and service quality as the highest-leverage investment, more so than comparable spending on physical upgrades.',

    'hanoi.limitationsTitle': 'Limitations & Next Steps',
    'hanoi.limitationsP1': 'This analysis reflects Booking.com\'s own rating taxonomy and is limited to listings collected via the sampling strategy described above. It assumes the overall score isn\'t computed from criteria wildly different from the seven visible sub-scores, an assumption validated only at a spot-check level, not exhaustively. The Wi-Fi dimension was excluded due to high missingness, as noted above.',
    'hanoi.limitationsP2': 'Future work could explore district-level variation, price-tier segmentation, and how the Facilities/Staff gap shifts across different demand seasons.',

