    'ejoy.next': 'Next → TikTok IMC campaign',
    'ejoy.overviewTitle': 'Overview',
    'ejoy.overviewP1': 'This project was part of the Principles of Marketing course at Foreign Trade University (December 2025), assigned in collaboration with eJOY Learning. Our six-person team worked from Don Norman\'s Emotional Design framework, the visceral, behavioral, and reflective layers, to understand how learners actually feel while using eJOY\'s ecosystem: the app, webapp, browser extension, and main website.',
    'ejoy.overviewP2': 'I was involved from the start and contributed across several parts of the research, but my main work was facilitating and observing our focus group sessions, writing the methodology and focus-group findings sections of the final report, and proposing the mascot concept in our recommendations.',
    'ejoy.overviewP3': 'eJOY\'s brief came down to one underlying question: how could the platform feel less like something users had to push through, and more like something they wanted to come back to?',
    'ejoy.researchTitle': 'The Research Question',
    'ejoy.researchP1': 'From that brief, we narrowed the research to four questions: what emotions learners experience across eJOY\'s products, what in the product makes them feel engaged versus bored, what \'core emotion\' sustains long-term motivation, and how those patterns could translate into concrete changes across the visceral, behavioral, and reflective layers.',
    'ejoy.researchP2': 'To answer these, the team combined ethnographic observation of real study sessions, two rounds of focus groups, learning diaries, and competitive benchmarking against Duolingo and HelloChinese. My part of this was the focus group.',
    'ejoy.focusGroupTitle': 'The Focus Group',
    'ejoy.focusGroupP1': 'Two rounds of focus groups, each with learners aged 18 to 25, formed the core of our qualitative research. I was directly involved in running and observing these sessions, taking notes not just on what people said, but on hesitations, half-finished sentences, and the moments where someone\'s tone shifted.',
    'ejoy.focusGroupP2': 'What stuck with me most wasn\'t anything anyone said outright. It was how differently people answered early in a session versus later. At first, most responses were polite and a little rehearsed, the kind of answer you\'d give if you wanted to sound like a \'good learner.\' As people relaxed, the answers got messier and more honest: frustration about feeling behind, guilt about skipping days, small embarrassment about having given up on other apps before.',
    'ejoy.focusGroupP3': 'Getting to that second layer wasn\'t automatic. It depended on how the session was facilitated and how much space was left for people to move past the first, safer answer. That gap, between what people say when they know they\'re being observed and what they actually feel, is something I kept thinking about for the rest of the project.',
    'ejoy.findingsTitle': 'What We Found',
    'ejoy.findingsP1': 'Across the focus groups and learning diaries, a clear emotional pattern emerged: pride and satisfaction after completing something tangible, followed by frustration or boredom once tasks became repetitive or mismatched to the learner\'s level. A teammate\'s analysis of this pattern, what we called the \'Goldilocks zone,\' showed that this optimal point, challenging but achievable, was rarely hit in practice. Too easy, and learners disengaged; too hard, and they felt anxious rather than motivated.',
    'ejoy.findingsP2': 'The team\'s separate observational study of real study sessions pointed in the same direction: a large share of learners checked their phones at least once per session, and many described studying because they \'had to\' rather than because they wanted to, echoing the motivation gap we kept hearing about in the focus groups.',
    'ejoy.findingsP3': 'Across both threads, the same theme kept surfacing: progress that doesn\'t feel visible is discouraging, and learners want something that feels less like a scorekeeper and more like a companion on their side.',
    'ejoy.marketTitle': 'Market Context',
    'ejoy.marketIntro': 'To position our recommendations, we benchmarked eJOY against Duolingo and HelloChinese across Norman\'s three design layers. The resulting picture wasn\'t just about feature gaps, it pointed to where the broader market was heading.',
    'ejoy.swotStrengthsLabel': 'Strengths',
    'ejoy.swotWeaknessesLabel': 'Weaknesses',
    'ejoy.swotOpportunitiesLabel': 'Opportunities',
    'ejoy.swotThreatsLabel': 'Threats',
    'ejoy.swotStrengths': 'Reflective value through real media content.',
    'ejoy.swotWeaknesses': 'Cluttered UI, occasional technical bugs.',
    'ejoy.swotOpportunities': 'As users graduate from Duolingo\'s gamified basics, they seek deeper content. A specific churn from Duolingo flows into apps like HelloChinese or eJOY, and capturing this post-Duolingo market is a major opportunity. There\'s also room to use LLMs beyond chat, to dynamically generate curriculum based on user interests (for example, a reading lesson built from a K-pop news article), and to build features that support the collaborative behaviors observed in the ethnography, like synchronous study rooms or shared vocab lists.',
    'ejoy.swotThreats': 'Duolingo is expanding into math, music, and advanced courses, encroaching on serious-study territory. As ChatGPT becomes a default tutor, standalone language apps risk irrelevance unless they offer structured pedagogy that raw AI doesn\'t. And the biggest competitor may not be another app at all, but TikTok: with attention spans dropping toward 8 seconds, lessons longer than 10 minutes face high abandonment.',
    'ejoy.recommendationsTitle': 'Recommendations',
    'ejoy.recommendationsP1': 'One of the recommendations I proposed was a mascot. The idea came from comparing eJOY\'s interface to Duolingo\'s: eJOY\'s current design felt clean but generic, the kind of interface that could belong to almost any app, while Duolingo\'s owl has become inseparable from its brand. A hand-crafted character that reacts to a learner\'s progress, puzzled when they get something wrong, celebratory after a streak, felt like a way to give the product a personality the current design lacks, and to make the \'companion\' role learners kept describing in the focus groups feel more concrete.',
    'ejoy.recommendationsP2': 'The rest of the recommendations followed the same shift: from competing on content volume to offering the most emotionally sustainable learning journey. That meant warmer \'support\' colors instead of alert reds, a Focus Mode to reduce clutter, progress shown as a journey rather than a leaderboard, and in-app prompts that sound less like warnings and more like a friend checking in, for example, swapping a streak-loss warning for something like \'The app feels quiet without you, ready for a 5-minute session?\'',
    'ejoy.reflectionTitle': 'Reflection',
    'ejoy.reflectionP1': 'Looking back, the part of this project that stayed with me wasn\'t any single finding, it was how much our eventual analysis depended on getting past the first, polite layer of user responses. It\'s easy to build a clean narrative out of focus group transcripts and call it \'the user\'s pain point,\' but the gap between what a team concludes and what users are actually struggling with can be large, and it\'s not always visible in the data alone. That tension, between a tidy analysis and messy reality, is something I expect to run into again in product and data work. This was the first time I felt it directly, rather than just reading about it.',

